Interesting survey.  I am in Kansas and we do not have time-of-use metering (currently at least). But penetration of EVs is still very small (even in my college town, sadly). FWIW, I'm not a believer in V2G, since it adds wear on the battery, and I like to keep cars for 12+ years.  My current EV is a PHEV, but I use it 100% in EV mode, unless I need to go cross-country :-)

I like what you’re trying to do, and I may be interested in one of these smart charging plans at some point. However, at the moment I have a unique charging situation in that I’m airline crew and live 2 hours from the airport. Therefore I depart for work with a 90% charge and return home after charging at an airport lot with 80% (the airport elevation is about 1,000ft higher than where I live so I use less energy going back home). 

I’m not interested in vehicle to grid as I feel the added charging cycles would degrade the life of my vehicle battery faster.

Lets get the fundamentals right before we advance tech for the sake of tech. 

Priorities:

1. Make EVs more affordable by providing better incentives for new and used vehicles. 
2 Build out the grid to handle pervasive EV use. Ensure this includes more renewable energy. 
3. Build out the charge infrastructure with government mandated industry STANDARD plugs and no brand use restrictions. This must include legislation that subsidizes buildout regardless of US material and labor content.
4. Government grants to develop improved battery safety and utility. 

5. National initiative to evolve from BEV to HFC powered transportation.  Grants for development of an HFC energy model including clean generation and distribution of H2.

I hate talking about charge levels in miles. My vehicle is EPA rated for 260, but I can pull nearly 400 as I drive gently and rarely use highways. I also never charge over 70% unless I plan on driving somewhere aside from my commute.

I have no objection to a grid controlled charge, but my schedule often changes and I need to adapt a bit. What I don't like from the scenarios is the spread in the min/max charges, and the milage based (or percent) charge level.  I would be happier with a KW based allocation, where I could manage my battery level and driving habits.  Something like an agreement to get up to 5KW weekdays at a reduced rate when plugged from 6PM to 6AM, and a normal or somewhat higher rate above that.

I don't think most people with home chargers care WHEN their car charges, so long as it gets them a charge.  Discounts are just icing on the cake.

You didn't ask about solar charging of my EV. Since my home has a solar array, my EV charging is effectively free. I have my charging scheduled during the highest amount of solar power, during the day. First my solar batteries are refilled, then my EV, and then anything left over goes to the grid. And since my overage of power is applied as a credit to my electric bill, this also reduces any grid cost. I've also heavily reduced my dependence on natural gas, converting the majority of power usage to electric.  Because of these factors, I don't need any of these programs or options.

The only reason I'm not interested in V2G it's because I worry about the additional wear and tear on the car battery. I think it's a great idea though. When batteries get better, I'd like to revisit the idea.
